Sec. 46-1. - Purpose and findings. The board of commissioners finds that signs provide an important medium through which individuals may convey a variety of non-commercial and commercial messages. However, left completely unregulated, signs can become a threat to public safety as a traffic hazard and detriment to property values and to Lumpkin County's overall public welfare as an aesthetic nuisance. By enacting this chapter, the board of commissioners intends to: A. Balance the rights of individuals to convey their messages through signs and the right of the public to be protected against the unrestricted proliferation of signs; B. Further the objectives of the Lumpkin County Comprehensive Plan; C. Protect the public health, safety, and welfare; D. Reduce traffic and pedestrian hazards; E. Maintain and enhance the visual environment, and preserve the right of the citizens to enjoy Lumpkin County's scenic beauty; F. Protect property values by minimizing possible adverse effects and visual blight caused by signs; G. Avoid the harmful aspects of the unrestricted proliferation of signs; H. Promote economic development; and I. Ensure the fair and consistent enforcement of sign regulations. (Res. No. 2017-66, exh. A, 9-19-2017; Res. No. 2017-71, exh. A, 10-17-2017) Sec. 46-2. - Applicability and severance. The regulations set forth below shall apply to all the unincorporated portions of the county. Within the unincorporated portions of the county no sign shall be erected or maintained unless it is in compliance with this chapter. In the event that a court should adjudge any part of this chapter a violation of the Georgia or United States Constitutions or any other provision of law, it is the specific intent of the board of commissioners that the offending provision or provisions be stricken from this chapter and the remainder of this chapter stay in effect to regulate signs on property within Lumpkin County. (Res. No. 2017-66, exh. A, 9-19-2017; Res. No. 2017-71, exh. A, 10-17-2017) Sec. 46-3. - Definitions. A. Address sign. Sign displaying the street address of the property. B. Billboard. Any sign that exceeds any dimension listed in section 46-7.B.2. C. Construction sign. A temporary sign erected on premises where construction for which a permit is required is taking place. D. Directory sign. Any sign located on developed premises, adjacent to exits, entrances, driveways, or off-street parking facilities. E. Freestanding sign. A sign that is not mounted on a principal building. F. Marquee sign. A sign that: 1. Is attached to a canopy or covered structure projecting from and supported by a building; and 2. Does not extend above or below such canopy or structure. G. Monument sign. A freestanding sign that is detached from a building and having a solid support structure. H. Nonconforming sign. Any sign that does not conform to the provisions of this Code and was legal when originally erected. I. Portable sign. A sign which is not permanently affixed by rigid structures to a permanent, concrete foundation or building; including any sign mounted on a vehicle, trailer, or other device designed to be moved periodically from place to place. J. Residentially used lot. A parcel of land that has on it one or more single family dwelling units. K. Roof sign. A sign projecting over the coping of a flat roof, or wholly or partially over the ridge of a gable, hip, or gambrel roof, and supported by or attached to the roof. L. Sign. A surface (or series of surfaces connected to a common supporting structure) on which is displayed an announcement, name, illustration, symbol or insignia used to inform the public or to identify, advertise or promote the interest of any person. M. Sign area. The area of the smallest rectangle within which all elements of a flat sign are contained (a flat sign being one with two display surfaces facing exactly opposite directions, or one display surface if against the wall of a building); or the maximum projected surface area (projected in one direction) of any other sign. 1. Supporting structures for signs shall not be counted in the sign area, provided such supporting structures consist of posts, hangers, or brackets of the minimum number and size necessary to support the sign. A wall or fence on which a sign is mounted shall not be counted in the sign area, provided it serves primarily to enclose, divide, or protect an area. 2. Supporting structures of natural finish brick masonry, stone masonry, or wood shall not be counted in the sign area, provided that: a. Such structures do not extend more than one foot above or two feet beyond the ends of the sign; b. The height of the combined sign and supporting structure does not exceed the maximum height allowed in this chapter; and c. The area of the combined sign and supporting structure does not exceed twice the area of the sign itself. N. Subdivision sign. Any sign identifying the entrance of a subdivision and located at the entrance of a subdivision. O. Temporary event. An activity having a specific duration or the end of which is related to a specific action, usually lasting for only a few days or months at a time. Temporary events include, but are not limited to, such activities as: 1. Special business promotions, such as, but not limited to, "grand openings," "close-out sales," carnivals and seasonal sales events. 2. A special event by a civic, philanthropic, educational or religious organization, such as a community fair or religious assembly. 3. An election cycle. P. Temporary sign. A display, sign, or banner with or without a structural frame, not permanently mounted, and intended to be displayed for only a limited time. (see section 46-8) Q. Vehicular sign. Any sign placed, mounted, painted on or affixed to a motor vehicle, freight, flatbed, storage trailer or other conveyance when same are placed or parked in such a manner as to be viewed or intended to be viewed from the public right-of-way. R. Wall sign. A sign which is mounted on the facade of the structure, is in a plane parallel to the wall (i.e., does not project at an angle to the wall), and does not project more than 12 inches from the wall. S. Window sign. A sign placed on or visible only through a window, display case, or entry door of a building. (Res. No. 2017-66, exh. A, 9-19-2017; Res. No. 2017-71, exh. A, 10-17-2017) Sec. 46-4. - General. A. Permit required. A permit shall be required for the erection, alteration or reconstruction of any sign unless otherwise noted and shall be issued by the planning department in accordance with these regulations. B. Materials and maintenance. Signs must be constructed of durable materials, maintained in good condition, and not permitted to become dilapidated. C. Freestanding signs. Unless otherwise specifically permitted by this chapter, the maximum height of any freestanding sign shall be ten feet. Maximum sign areas shall apply to each face separately, but no freestanding sign shall have more than two faces. Where two sign faces are located in a "V" formation, the angle between the two sign faces shall not be greater than 60 degrees. D. Wall and projecting signs. Wall signs attached flat against a wall may not extend more than 12 inches from the wall. Signs attached at an angle to a wall may not extend outward from the wall of a building more than five feet and may not be located closer than 18 inches to a vertical plane at the street curb line. In no case shall signs project beyond property lines. E. Sign setbacks. In no case will a sign be placed where it would obscure vision at a street or driveway intersection. F. Obsolete signs. A sign becomes obsolete if it is allowed to become dilapidated or is not maintained. Obsolete signs must be removed or repaired by property owner, developer, or former lessee of property upon which sign is located within 30 days after receipt of written notice from the planning department. G. Illumination. No sign shall be illuminated by lights that flash, move, change in intensity, or turn on intermittently; except that a digital display may change no more often than once, each 20 seconds, and shall be subject to the applicable lighting standards within this chapter. To prevent glare visible from a public street or adjoining property, the beam of any light shall be directed so as not to be visible beyond the sign at which it is directed, and the light source shall not be visible from any point on an adjacent property or the public right-of-way. H. Movement. No sign or part of a sign shall rotate, oscillate, or otherwise move or change in appearance, whether such motion is driven by wind, mechanical, electrical, or other means; except as provided under "Illumination" above. (Res. No. 2017-66, exh. A, 9-19-2017; Res. No. 2017-71, exh. A, 10-17-2017) Sec. 46-5. - Signs that do not require a permit. (reference section 46-6.d.) The following types of signs do not require application for a sign permit and are considered to have a general permit, provided that such signs are erected and maintained in compliance with all applicable conditions: A. Directory sign with a maximum area not to exceed six square feet, maximum height five feet and setback a minimum of one foot from the edge of the pavement and off any public right-of-way. One directory sign is allowed per access point. B. Construction sign with a maximum area not to exceed 32 square feet, a maximum height of eight feet, and shall be at least ten feet from the edge of the adjacent pavement. C. Bulletin boards for any use, not exceeding 32 square feet. D. One unlighted identification sign for a permitted home occupation, provided that such sign is attached to the structure in which the home occupation is conducted, and has a maximum sign area of four square feet. E. Temporary signs with a maximum area not to exceed 16 square feet and a maximum height of eight feet. These signs will be removed within seven days upon the completion of the temporary event. F. Flags, provided that: All flagpoles shall be maintained in good repair, so as not to constitute a threat to public safety. G. In addition to any other sign which requires a permit, signs are allowed as follows: 1. Individual signs up to ten square feet with a total sign area not exceeding 30 square feet; and 2. Shall be a maximum height of five feet with a minimum setback of five feet from side property lines. (Res. No. 2017-66, exh. A, 9-19-2017; Res. No. 2017-71, exh. A, 10-17-2017) Sec. 46-6. - Sign permits. A. Purpose. The purpose of this section is to provide a mechanism for reviewing applications for sign permits to ensure signs within the county comply with the standards of this chapter. B. Authority. The planning director is authorized to review and approve or disapprove an application for a sign permit pursuant to the procedures of this section and the standards of this chapter. C. Applicability. No sign, except those specified in subsection D below of this section for which a general permit has been granted, shall be erected, placed, reconstructed or structurally altered without the sign owner having first obtained a sign permit from the planning director, pursuant to the procedures in this section and the standards of this chapter. D. Signs for which a general permit has been granted. Pursuant to this chapter, a general permit has been granted for those signs listed in section 46-5, and no application for a sign permit is required so long as the standards of this chapter are met. E. Procedure. 1. Initial submission and review of application. Application for a sign permit shall be made on the form provided by the planning department, and shall be accompanied by the information and documents listed on the form and the fee as required by the board of commissioners. An application will only be deemed as sufficient when all required information and accompanying documents are received. 2. Action by planning director. Within ten business days after the application is determined sufficient, the planning director shall review the application in accordance with this section and determine whether the application complies with the standards in this chapter. 3. Approval. If the planning director finds that the application complies with the standards of this chapter, the planning director shall approve a sign permit. Any sufficient sign application for which no action has been taken after ten business days shall be deemed approved. 4. Fails to comply. If the planning director determines the application fails to comply with the standards of this chapter, the applicant shall be provided a notification with written comments, explaining why the application fails to comply with the standards. The applicant shall be provided an opportunity to submit a revised application. If a revised application is not resubmitted within 30 days of the date of notification, the application shall be considered withdrawn and subject to a new application and remittance of accompanying fees. The time for resubmission may be extended an additional 30 days, if requested prior to the original deadline for resubmittal. 5. Resubmittal. A revised application shall be resubmitted to the planning director and reviewed by the planning director within five business days after its resubmittal. The planning director shall approve or deny the application, based on the criteria in this chapter. F. Criteria. A sign permit shall be approved upon a finding that the applicant has demonstrated the application complies with the standards of this chapter. G. Expiration. If the work described in any sign permit has not been completed within one year from the date of issuance, the sign permit shall expire and become void. H. Amendments. A sign permit may be amended, extended, or modified only within the procedures established for its original approval. (Res. No. 2017-66, exh. A, 9-19-2017; Res. No. 2017-71, exh. A, 10-17-2017) Sec. 46-7. - Standards for permitted signs. The following signs shall be permitted, all other signs being specifically prohibited: A. Signs for which a general permit has been granted. B. Monument signs. One ground mounted monument sign shall be permitted on each lot, except that in the case of a corner lot, the provisions of this section shall apply separately to each street frontage. However, no sign on a corner lot shall be closer than 50 feet from the lot corner, defined by the lot lines extended. 1. The sign structure shall be constructed of materials similar to that used in the facade of the principal building. 2. Dimensional standards for monument signs are set forth in the table below:
C. Wall signs and marquee signs. One wall sign or marquee sign shall be permitted for each building or for each tenant in a multi-tenant building. The maximum sign area shall be 20 percent of the area of the wall. No wall sign shall be placed within three feet of another wall sign. D. Master plan for signs in multi-tenant developments. For all multi-tenant buildings or developments, a coordinated program of wall signs shall be developed and approved by the county at the time of site plan approval. The signage master plan shall specify the sign type, design, height, colors, illumination, and other specifications to give a coordinated appearance to the building or development. The county's review and approval of the signage master plan shall be based on the compatibility of the proposed signage with the siting and architecture of the subject building or development and the compatibility of the signage with surrounding land uses. E. Additional signage permitted for service and fueling stations are as follows: 1. One sign per canopy facade per public street frontage with a maximum of 16 square feet shall be permitted, provided that the area used to display this information is no larger than eight square feet and does not extend above or below the edge of the canopy. 2. Spreader bars (signs located under canopy over pump islands) shall be limited to no more than two signs per spreader bar, not to exceed four square feet per sign. However, total square footage for all spreader bars shall not exceed 24 square feet. (Res. No. 2017-66, exh. A, 9-19-2017; Res. No. 2017-71, exh. A, 10-17-2017) Sec. 46-8. - Standards for temporary signs. A total of one additional sign per street frontage, which may be either of the following, shall be permitted for the duration of a temporary event: 1. One non-illuminated temporary sign, flag or banner, not exceeding six square feet in area nor four feet in height in a single-family residentially used area and not exceeding 32 square feet in area nor 12 feet in height in a multifamily or non-residentially used area. 2. Signage shall be limited through the duration of the temporary event and shall be removed within seven days upon conclusion of the temporary event. 3. No temporary signs will be allowed on public right-of ways. (Res. No. 2017-66, exh. A, 9-19-2017; Res. No. 2017-71, exh. A, 10-17-2017) Sec. 46-9. - Prohibited signs. Notwithstanding any other provision of this chapter, the following types of signs shall be prohibited anywhere in the unincorporated areas of Lumpkin County: A. Signs imitating warning signals. No sign shall display intermittent lights resembling the flashing lights customarily used in traffic signals or in police, fire, ambulance or rescue vehicles, nor shall any sign use the words "stop," "danger," or any other word, phrase, symbol or character in a manner that might mislead or confuse an automobile or other vehicular driver. B. Signs within road, street or highway right-of-way. No signs whatsoever, whether temporary or permanent, except traffic signs and signals and information signs erected by a public agency, are permitted within any road right-of-way. C. Signs painted on or attached to trees, fence posts, utility poles, rocks or other natural features on public owned property or right-of-way are prohibited. D. Fluttering ribbons and banners. Fluttering ribbons and banners and similar devices are prohibited within the front yard setback. This restriction shall not apply to flags. E. Billboards. Billboard signs shall be prohibited, except as required by Georgia or federal law. F. Roof signs. No sign shall be permitted that is mounted on or extends into the air above any roof surface of a building. A sign may be mounted against a parapet of uniform height around the perimeter of a building but may not extend above the parapet. G. Portable signs. No portable sign shall be permitted unless it qualifies as a temporary sign and complies with all applicable requirements for such signs under this chapter. H. Signs within visibility clearance areas. No freestanding sign or flag between a height of two and one-half feet and ten feet shall be installed and maintained within the visibility clearance area defined by: 1. Points 25 feet distant from the intersection of any two of the following: a. Any public street(s); b. Any driveway for other than single- or two-family use. 2. A straight line connecting those two points. I. Vehicular sign. Are prohibited except when such signs are: 1. Actively being used to transport persons, goods or services in the normal course of business; 2. Parked in an inconspicuous area; or 3. Actively being used for storage of construction materials for, and on the same lot with a bona fide construction project for which building and other applicable permits have been issued and where construction is underway and provided said conveyances are located within designated storage areas. (Res. No. 2017-66, exh. A, 9-19-2017; Res. No. 2017-71, exh. A, 10-17-2017) Sec. 46-10. - Nonconforming signs. A building or freestanding sign that lawfully existed on the effective date of this Code may continue to be used, except that the nonconforming sign: 1. Shall not be repaired, rebuilt, replaced, or altered after damage or removal exceeding 50 percent of the sign structure. 2. Shall not be enlarged or altered in a way that increases its nonconformity. 3. May be altered for a change in use, change in ownership, or change in business name. (Res. No. 2017-66, exh. A, 9-19-2017; Res. No. 2017-71, exh. A, 10-17-2017) Sec. 46-11. - Administrative and enforcement. A. Administrative powers. The board of commissioners shall administer and enforce the provisions of these sign regulations, and the planning director is hereby appointed to exercise the powers prescribed by this sign regulation. These powers shall include, but shall not be limited to accepting and processing applications, conducting inspections, issuing permits and instituting enforcement actions through one or more employees; subject to the right of appeal to the board of commissioners as otherwise provided by these sign regulations. B. Enforcement. The erection or maintenance by any person of any sign for which a permit is required by these sign regulations without a valid permit or renewal thereof issued by the county is unlawful. In addition to the remedies provided for in these sign regulations or that may otherwise exist under the laws of the state, the county is authorized to pursue all equitable remedies and criminal and civil sanctions available. 1. Notification of violations. Such notification shall be made by certified letter from the planning department or an authorized representative of the board of commissioners to the applicant's or individual's last known address and shall provide the violator ten days from the date of the letter to bring the sign into compliance. The notice shall be deemed sufficient upon mailing to the last known address. 2. Revocation of permits and licenses. Any person failing to comply with any provision of these sign regulations shall be subject to revocation of the business license, work permit or other authorization for the conduct of business and associated work activities within the unincorporated areas of the county. 3. Stop work orders. Any person failing to comply with any provision of these sign regulations shall be subject to a stop work order. Upon receipt of the stop work order, work on any project that is being performed in violation of these sign regulations shall immediately stop. Such notice shall be in writing and shall be given to the owner of the property, owner of the sign, the owner's authorized agent or the person in charge of the activity on the property, and shall state the conditions under which work may resume. If an emergency exists, then no written notice shall be required. 4. Violation of permit. If through inspection it is determined that a person engaged in any activity covered by these sign regulations has failed to comply with the sign regulations or the conditions of the permit issued, then a written notice to comply shall be served upon that person. The notice shall set forth the measures necessary to achieve compliance and shall be subject to forfeiture. 5. Permit suspension or revocation. The permit issued hereunder may be suspended or revoked by the county upon a finding that the holder is in violation of the permit or any portion of these sign regulations. 6. Violations. Any person violating the provisions of this article may be issued a citation and, upon conviction, may be assessed a fine of not less than $100.00 and not exceeding $1,000.00 for each offense. Each day of a continuing violation shall constitute a separate offense. In addition to any other remedies, the Lumpkin County Board of Commissioners may address any violation of this article by seeking injunction or other civil action. Such proceeding may be instituted without the necessity of showing the lack of an adequate remedy at law. Any one or more of the foregoing enforcement provisions may be utilized separately or in combination to achieve compliance with these sign regulations. C. Variance and appeals. 1. Variance to the sign standards may be requested for approval by the planning commission. Such requests shall be submitted to the planning department to be placed on the agenda for action by the planning commission. 2. Any decision of the planning director may be appealed to the planning commission by the applicant. Planning commission decision may be appealed to the board of commissioners by the applicant. Request for appeal of planning director or planning commission decisions must be submitted to the planning department within ten days of the decision. All appeals must be in writing and must specify the grounds of the appeal. (Res. No. 2017-66, exh. A, 9-19-2017; Res. No. 2017-71, exh. A, 10-17-2017)
